                        "customWidth": "50",
                        "name": "metric - 18"
                      },
                      {
                        "type": 1,
                        "content": {
                          "json": "** Recommendations - Logical/physical Replication Lag**\r\n\r\n**NOTE**   \r\n\r\n** Any oldest transaction on replica server will block the vacuum activity on primary with hot_standby_feedback=on. With this setting, replica will keep <br>primary informed about the oldest open transaction and VACUUM operation on primary will not clear dead rows which are required by replica transactions.**\r\n\r\n\r\n**Short Term:**\r\n\r\n* You may have inactive logical/physical replication slots leading to lag.\r\n\r\n* The  xmin column in the pg_replication_slots view has the oldest transaction needed on the replica server.\r\n\r\n**Run the below on primary to get the xmin value for replica server**\r\n\r\n\tSELECT slot_name, slot_type, database, xmin, active\r\n\tFROM pg_replication_slots\r\n\tORDER BY age(xmin) DESC;\r\n\r\n**Run the below on replica server to get xmin value for long-running sessions**\r\n\r\n\tSELECT pid, datname, usename, state, backend_xmin\r\n\tFROM pg_stat_activity\r\n\tWHERE backend_xmin IS NOT NULL\r\n\tORDER BY age(backend_xmin) DESC;\r\n\r\nYou can use pg_cancel_backend() or pg_terminate_backend() function to cancel the active query or terminate the backend connection <br> for long-running sessions that are blocking vacuum activity on primary.\r\n\r\n**Long Term :**\r\n\r\n1. Long running transactions can increase the lag.It is advised to have `statement_timeout` set on the server or splitting a very large transaction into smaller chunks.The idea is to have transactions running lesser amount of time.\r\n\r\n2. Tune the queries and look into table design for optimal query performance.\r\n\r\n3. Move to a higher SKU for better performance.\r\n\r\n4. Make sure primary and secondary servers are on the same SKU.\r\n\r\n5. For logical replicaiton, try to create multiple replication slots and spread the workload to use multiple slots so that replication can catch up with workload. Reference to pglogical extension is: [Flexible Server](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/postgresql/flexible-server/concepts-logical) \r\n\r\n6. For logical replicaiton, Consider tuning server parameters like `max_worker_processes`,`max_replication_slots`,`max_sync_workers_per_subscription`. Please test and evaluate carefully before making the changes.\r\n",
                          "style": "info"
                        },
                        "name": "text - 40"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  "name": "LogicalPhysicalLag"
                },
                {
                  "type": 1,
                  "content": {
                    "json": "- **Inactive Replicaiton Slots**\r\n\t- Replication slots are used to keep track of the progress of replication between the primary and standby servers.\r\n\t- If a replication slot is inactive or has not been used for a long time, it can prevent Autovacuum from reclaiming space in the affected tables.\r\n\t- These issues include increased disk usage due to WAL files being retained, reduced replication performance due to excessive replication slots being maintained.",
                    "style": "info"
                  },
                  "name": "text - 11 - Copy"
                },
                {
                  "type": 12,
                  "content": {
                    "version": "NotebookGroup/1.0",
                    "groupType": "editable",
                    "loadType": "explicit",
                    "loadButtonText": "Show Inactive Replication Slots",
                    "items": [
                      {
                        "type": 1,
                        "content": {
                          "json": "\r\n**Recommendations**\r\n\r\nTo detect inactive and physical replication slots in PostgreSQL, you can use the following query:\r\n\r\n```pgsql \r\nSELECT slot_name, active, restart_lsn FROM pg_replication_slots;\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis query selects all replication slots in the current database, along with their status (active or inactive) and the last restart LSN. You can use this information to identify inactive or unused replication slots that may be causing issues with replication or impacting database performance.\r\n\r\nTo mitigate these issues, you can follow these steps:\r\n\r\nIdentify inactive or unused replication slots using the query above.\r\n\r\nIf a replication slot is inactive or unused, you can either drop it or activate it depending on your requirements. Dropping a replication slot will remove it permanently, while activating it will allow it to be used for replication again.\r\n\r\nIf you have identified any physical replication slots that are not in use, you can remove them by stopping the associated replication slot worker process and dropping the slot using the following \r\n\r\n```pgsql\r\nSELECT pg_drop_replication_slot('slot_name');\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
                          "style": "info"
                        },
                        "name": "text - 17"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  "name": "Inactiveslots"
                }
              ]
            },
            "name": "Replication lag and inactive replication slots"
          },
          {
            "type": 12,
            "content": {
              "version": "NotebookGroup/1.0",
              "groupType": "editable",
              "title": "Long running transactions on replica servers with hot_standby_feedback=ON",
              "expandable": true,
              "expanded": true,
              "items": [
                {
                  "type": 1,
                  "content": {
                    "json": "- Long running transactions on a replica server can block Autovacuum, as they hold locks on the affected tables and prevent vacuum and analyze operations from proceeding.\r\n- If hot_standby_feedback is turned on, the primary server may prioritize sending WAL records for these long running transactions to the replica server, causing further delays and blocking Autovacuum even more.\r\n",
                    "style": "info"
                  },
                  "name": "text - 12"
                },
                {
                  "type": 12,
                  "content": {
                    "version": "NotebookGroup/1.0",
                    "groupType": "editable",
                    "loadType": "explicit",
                    "loadButtonText": "Show Information for Long running transactions on replica servers",
                    "items": [
                      {
                        "type": 1,
                        "content": {
                          "json": "### Absence of Read Replicas: No Further Investigation Required\r\nAs there are no read replicas available for the server, there is no need to further investigate this matter.",
                          "style": "success"
                        },
                        "customWidth": "50",
                        "conditionalVisibility": {
                          "parameterName": "IsServerHavingReplica",
                          "comparison": "isEqualTo",
                          "value": "No"
                        },
                        "name": "text - 82 - Copy - Copy"
                      },
                      {
                        "type": 1,
                        "content": {
                          "json": "The Transaction ID causing the issue may be associated with a **long-running session on the replica** server. This can occur when a transaction on the replica server holds the xmin horizon, preventing autovacuum from removing dead tuples on the primary server. To verify if the xmin belongs to a replica server transaction, you can execute the following command on the primary server:<br><br>\r\n**SELECT max(age(backend_xmin)) FROM pg_stat_replication;** <br><br>\r\nThis will show you the age of the oldest xmin horizon on the replica server, which can help identify if a long-running transaction is the cause of the issue."
                        },
                        "conditionalVisibility": {
                          "parameterName": "IsServerHavingReplica",
                          "comparison": "isEqualTo",
                          "value": "Yes"
                        },
                        "name": "text - 0"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  "name": "group - 12"
                }
              ]
            },
            "name": "Long running transactions on replica servers with hot_standby_feedback=ON"
          }
